tablished and tested as far as we can."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c345be66512ee14f08acd1e27e387c4a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1578,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1578/rumtscho","reputation":1534,"display_name":"rumtscho","accept_rate":70},"score":0,"post_id":39580,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445328100,"comment_id":66709,"body":"Oh, and another thing: there are no arguments in my answer, except the one connection from humor to laughter. I needed this space to simply explain the claim of the theory. I did not attempt to reproduce any of the <i>evidence<\/i> for it - if somebody can do this in a reasonable length of text, I am not this person. The book I am speaking of uses 3 pages to explain the above, and another 370 to present arguments for it. So of course you won&#39;t feel convinced of the theory being true just by reading this answer - don&#39;t expect this, or take it as evidence that the theory is not true."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":39580,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445328432,"comment_id":66710,"body":"@rumptscho People have seldom investigated laughter because it&#39;s not a &quot;problem&quot; to be solved rather than because it&#39;s impossible to test. To leap to philosophical reasonable hypotheses as the absolute truth <i>before<\/i> we have pushed the limits of empiricism seems premature. This isn&#39;t exactly theoretical multi-verse physics yet, it&#39;s just messy neuroscience! As you say, the mind-space theory <i>fits<\/i> many humorous situations; Platos world of forms <i>fitted<\/i> really well too. Remain skeptical until there is conclusive data. <b><i>Why should we be afraid to say that we don