 (about 1--3% per day; see <a href=\"https://books.google.se/books?id=I77jj6EWuT8C&amp;pg=PA17\" rel=\"nofollow\">this book<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p>And yes, vitamin C is very important in defense against free radicals; it is <a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/86/16/6377.short\" rel=\"nofollow\">considered the major water-soluble antioxidant<\/a> in humans. <\/p>\n","answer_id":42789,"question_id":42763,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42763/does-vitamin-c-decrease-after-reacting-with-oxygen-free-radicals","last_activity_date":1456667703,"creation_date":1454009080,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does vitamin C decrease after reacting with oxygen free radicals?","body":"<p>From the research that I have done, I know that antioxidants such as vitamin c donate electrons to oxygen free radicals and effectively neutralize them. They themselves do not become free radicals as they are stable in both forms.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, would it be correct to say that after the vitamin C is oxidized(giving electrons to free radicals) so much that it can no longer give any more electrons(not sure what the actual limit is):<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>What happens to vitamin C (does it get broken down and therefore\ndecrease) <\/li>\n<li>Is it any useful in destroying free radicals?<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","question_id":42763,"tags":["vitamins","dna-damage"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":29,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1454049628},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/71e3da221ac29ea8a2ffeba372820da4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17632/bob-smith","reputation":68,"display_name":"Bob Smith","accept_rate":89},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43780/oncotic-osmotic-pressure-in-the-blood-pressure","last_activity_date":1456667411,"creation_date":1456667411,"answer_count":0,"title":"Oncotic (Osmotic Pressure) in the blood pressu