od and funny question. Cats are not striped? But cats are with black parts and white parts. This can be quite pretty. What aren&#39;t humans generally like this? There is a rare case where humans <i>do<\/i> get parts of different colors: <i>chimeras<\/i>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":35661,"edited":false,"creation_date":1435831672,"comment_id":58568,"body":"@Farzad you should really edit this question to make it suitable."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dee334d11391632e5c2ba4709d942c96?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":16512,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16512/nicolas-barbulesco","reputation":125,"display_name":"Nicolas Barbulesco"},"score":0,"post_id":35665,"edited":false,"creation_date":1436873375,"comment_id":59568,"body":"Why would black and white bands require genetic imprinting? How do cats have black and white parts?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":35665,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dee334d11391632e5c2ba4709d942c96?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":16512,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16512/nicolas-barbulesco","reputation":125,"display_name":"Nicolas Barbulesco"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1436874611,"comment_id":59570,"body":"because the cells in the offspring would need to be able to differentiate between the paternally and maternally inherited allele to be able to organise them in to stripes"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1435993926,"creation_date":1435668792,"body":"<p>Skin colour is determined by additive effects. That is, the amount of pigment is determined additively by the genes. For the basic genetics of it I will give a simple example, which is just illustrative and a gross oversimplification, it's probably much more complex (many loci all acting at once).<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Imaginary example:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Suppose skin colour is affected by a single locus (at one position) within the DNA, which determines the amount of pigment produced. At this locus there are two alleles within a population, that is two versions of the DNA (e.g. ACGTCCATT and GACTTAACT are different DNA sequences). Allele one ($A_1$) produces a small amount of pigment, and allele 2 ($A_2$) produces a large amount. Thus people with $A_1 A_1$ genotype (people are diploid, i.e. they get a version from each parent) have light skin, $A_2 A_2$ genotypes have dark skin, and $A_1 A_2$ have an intermediate skin colour. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Analogy<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>This is analogous to mixing fruit juice with water - if you mix <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ribena\" rel=\"nofollow\">blackcurrant cordial<\/a> with water the colour is determined by the proportions. If you put out two bottles, one with cordial and one with water, allow two people to randomly choose a bottle, and use their choices to mix a glass of drink, 50% of the time you will end up with 1/2 water mixed with 1/2 cordial, while 25% of the time just a glass full of water, and the remaining 25% of the time just a glass full of cordial.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Why stripes don't occur<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><em>Note: although stripes occur in animals including humans (see chris' answer), it's not I'm the way your question insinuates<\/em> <\/p>\n\n<p>For stripes to occur you would have to have structure in the skin with two different types of skin cell, where bands/stripes of type occur - alternating between expressing the allele inherited from the mother, and that inherited from the father. That would require structure in the skin and something called genomic imprinting so parent of origin could be a factor. <\/p>\n\n<p>The analogy with the glass of cordial is what going on in each cell, for stripes you would have to have organised and alternating clusters of glasses (cells) which get their contents determined by one individuals choice of cordial, with the selector alternating with the cluster of glasses.<\/p>\n","answer_id":35665,"question_id":35661,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1435993926},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":7,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-Q7qa9X6M8oE/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAACB4/NnR8G0JQGZc/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16041,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16041/solarlunix","reputation":1965,"display_name":"SolarLunix","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":35668,"edited":false,"creation_date":1435956514,"comment_id":58694,"body":"And aren&#39;t cat pigments controlled by one gene?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dee334d11391632e5c2ba4709d942c96?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":16512,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16512/nicolas-barbulesco","reputation":125,"display_name":"Nicolas Barbulesco"},"score":0,"post_id":35668,"edited":false,"creation_date":1436870844,"comment_id":59566,"body":"What about cats?"}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1435672604,"creation_date":1435671110,"body":"<p>The reason that there are no stripes when black and white people get babies is the fact that the number of pigment cells is the same for black and white people. What is different is the amount of pigment produced, and it will be different in the kids as well (lighter than the dark parent, darker than the light parent) See references 1 and 2 for details on the melanocyte density. Skin color is a multigenic trait, so the genetic background of both parents and their effects on pigmentation come into full play here.<\/p>\n\n<p>Besides this effect, humans do have stripes, although they are mostly not visible. They are called <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaschko%27s_lines\">Blaschko's lines<\/a> and look like below:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/QN3OQ.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>These develop from the migration pattern of the melanocytes (and their precursor cells) in the developing embryo. They can get visible in some rare genetic conditions or by diseases. See reference 3 for a more popular explanation and reference 4 for a review on this field.<\/p>\n\n<p>References:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"http://rstb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/252/779/447\">The Regional Anatomy of the Human Integument with Special Reference\nto the Distribution of Hair Follicles, Sweat Glands and Melanocytes<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/9780470987100.ch3/summary\">General Biology of Mammalian Pigmentation<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://scienceblogs.com/pharyngula/2010/08/12/blaschkos-lines/\">Blaschko\u2019s Lines<\/a><\/li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.filedropper.com/bolognia1994\">Lines of Blaschko.<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":35668,"question_id":35661,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1435672604}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/35661/why-a-striped-baby-is-not-the-result-of-a-white-and-a-black-parent","last_activity_date":1456644774,"creation_date":1435664938,"answer_count":2,"title":"Why a striped baby is not the result of a white and a black parent?","body":"<p>Someone asked me:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>If a striped cat is the result of a white and a black cat, why the result of a white woman and a black man is not a striped child?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I know the answer. I also know that the result of a black cat and a white one is not a striped cat. But I'm looking for a simple answer. I'm looking for an explanation without a genetics background required. I'm looking for a metaphor or something similar. <\/p>\n","question_id":35661,"tags":["genetics"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":6,"is_answered":true,"view_count":370,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1435672314},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5b5440c34109e218b55c29d2450159ee?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6136/21joanna12","reputation":659,"display_name":"21joanna12","accept_rate":46},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/LVigb.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13338/eli-korvigo","reputation":548,"display_name":"Eli Korvigo","accept_rate":100},"score":4,"post_id":41207,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449176341,"comment_id":69768,"body":"Your brain, being the most oxygen-hungry part of your body, goes to <code>sleep-mode<\/code> and eventually dies due to insufficient ATP levels. Glycolysis (carried our by glial cells, not the neurons themselves) doesn&#39;t produce enough energy. You may want to read <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9778571\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TVDAK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type