"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16866/theforestecologist","reputation":1908,"display_name":"theforestecologist","accept_rate":14},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1456602321,"creation_date":1456601391,"body":"<p>This lizard is likely a <strong>Roughtail Rock Agama (<em>Stellagama stellio<\/em><\/strong> or <strong><em>Laudakia stellio<\/em>)<\/strong>. They are colloquially referred to as hardon (or hardun) lizards. <\/p>\n\n<p>According to <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stellagama\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Like many agamids, stellions can change color to express their moods. They bask on stone walls, rocks, and trees. They are usually found in rocky habitats, and are quite shy, being very ready to dive into cracks to hide from potential predators.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/nbqEA.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/nbqEA.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>More from <a href=\"http://natureisrael.com/creatures.html#lizz\" rel=\"nofollow\">natureisreal<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The most commonly seen local lizard where I live in central Israel is probably the roughtail rock agama (laudakia stellio stellio), known locally as a hardon or hardun. They are rather sinister looking with rough dark armoured skin, but perfectly harmless. If frightened they run away and hide in the crevice of a rock or tree, inflating their skin and opening their mouth wide to wedge themsevles into the space, making it impossible to dislodge them. Sometimes I see a large dark male surveying his territory from the top of the nearby water tower.More usually they are to be seen during the warmest times of day sunning themselves on rocks, to the extent that it seems that each rocks has its own resident hardon, and believe me, this country is full of rocks, and that makes for a lot of these lizards...<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Mjxow.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Mjxow.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a>\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/yjgr4.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/yjgr4.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":43760,"question_id":43758,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1456602321}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43758/lizard-spieces-identification","last_activity_date":1456609429,"creation_date":1456596826,"answer_count":1,"title":"Lizard spieces identification","body":"<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/oeswN.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/oeswN.jpg\" alt=\"\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>I managed to photograph a lizard in Haruvit Forest, Israel. I would like to know - what lizard species is this? Size appr. 20-25cm<\/p>\n","question_id":43758,"tags":["species-identification","herpetology"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":43760,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":37,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1456609429},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c6753cdc4182d3db8f25774c8527fc63?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21071,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21071/hephaes","reputation":58,"display_name":"hephaes"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3e5f0d71d85cff28bc4a479a1635bb7b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16371,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16371/matej-pribis","reputation":174,"display_name":"Matej Pribis"},"score":1,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c6753cdc4182d3db8f25774c8527fc63?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21071,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21071/hephaes","reputation":58,"display_name":"hephaes"},"score":0,"post_id":43768,"edited":false,"creation_date":1456633560,"comment_id":75832,"body":"Thx that is an excellent detailed answer 😆"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1456609206,"creation_date":1456609206,"body":"<p>Yes, dopamine receptors (D1-D5) are G protein coupled receptors,  which act primarily on adenylatecyclase (changing cAMP concentration, which activate proteinkinase A, which phosphorylates other proteins in turn such as CREB... you can find the pathway in the following article). D1 receptors activate adenylatecyclase, D2 inhibit its activity.<\/p>\n\n<p>I wouldn't say it directly alters the Ca2+ channel concentration per se, the article says however it can modify their state. <\/p>\n\n<p>According to <a href=\"http://pharmrev.aspetjournals.org/content/63/1/182.full\" rel=\"nofollow\">this<\/a> article, G proteins of these receptors could also have different effects (alternative effects through G-proteins such as activating phospholipase C, which results in IP3 formation which results in Ca2+ influx to cytoplasm from ER which acts on proteinkinase C) or new research suggest that it could also act through G protein-independent mechanisms via interactions with ion channels.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>specificity of the location (of the brain) that dopamine acts on controlled?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The idea is that cells with certain neurotransmitter may induce growth of cells with same transmitter, thus forming specific circuits. I don't know however how specifically this happens and how the cells communicate to form specific connections (like dopaminergic connection from substantia nigra to basal ganglia) during development. I'd bet on some morphogenes. Someone else might know better :) . <\/p>\n\n<p>Yes, dopamine is associated with addiction, as it's part of the reward system in brain. Many drugs inhibit its transport from synaptic cleft into the cells, which means prolonged activity, brain senses positive effects you can see when you've done something good (reward). <\/p>\n","answer_id":43768,"question_id":43752,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43752/how-can-dopamine-modulate-synaptic-strength","last_activity_date":1456609206,"creation_date":1456585340,"answer_count":1,"title":"How can dopamine modulate synaptic strength?","body":"<p>Does dopamine act on G protein coupled receptor, leading to more Ca2+ channels on the postsynaptic knob? <\/p>\n\n<p>Also, how is the specificity of the location (of the brain) that dopamine acts on controlled? Or is it controlled at all? Is this chemical associated with addiction? <\/p>\n","question_id":43752,"tags":["biochemistry","molecular-biology","neuroscience"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":43768,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":22,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/mzn9K.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15317,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15317/tox123","reputation":200,"display_name":"tox123"},"closed_date":1456612986,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43761/why-is-down-syndrome-more-common-than-other-trisomies","last_activity_date":1456602777,"creation_date":1456602777,"answer_count":0,"title":"Why is down syndrome more common than other trisomies?","body":"<p>Why is Down syndrome more common than say trisomy 18? Is chromosome 21 easier to replicate? Or is it because those babies are more viable?<\/p>\n","question_id":43761,"tags":["genetics","human-genetics","chromosome","polyploidy"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"duplicate","is_answered":false,"view_count":19,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0213abf0a1ecffcae01eceeea6ba2ff9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":22124,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22124/display-name","reputation":30,"display_name":"Display Name"},"closed_date":1456470596,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar