ng><em>Albizia julibrissin<\/em> (Persian silk tree)<\/strong> is doubly compound (AKA <strong><em>bipinnate<\/em><\/strong>) and has a conspicuous pink/white fluffy flower. This tree is an Asian native, but it's a commonly cultivated (and equally commonly escaped) plant in the U. S. Should be able to find it in numerous locations. Look in yards and along roads. <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Pqqz4.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Pqqz4.jpg\" alt=\"Albizia julibrissin\"><\/a>\n<a href=\"http://www.missouriplants.com/Pinkalt/Albizia_julibrissin_plant.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.missouriplants.com/Pinkalt/Albizia_julibrissin_plant.jpg<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>For native species: <strong><em>Gleditsia triacanthos<\/em> (honeylocust)<\/strong> is a fairly widespread (though uncommon) example of bipinnate leaves. Here is an image from Will Cook's wonderful <a href=\"http://www.carolinanature.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">website<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/A8b60.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/A8b60.jpg\" alt=\"Gleditsia triacanthos\"><\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":42531,"question_id":40003,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1453402105}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40003/doubly-compound-leaf-examples","last_activity_date":1456587289,"creation_date":1445978645,"answer_count":3,"title":"Doubly-compound leaf examples?","body":"<p>I've got a project where we collect leaves, classify them, etc. There are some required classifications. One of the requirements is to get a doubly-compound leaf. What are some trees that are doubly-compound? Please help! I have Hickory, but that's just compound, I think.<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit: I did try googling, but it's hard for me to know what's available in my region.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>From Comments:<\/strong> <em>I live in Tennessee, U.S.<\/em><\/p>\n","question_id":40003,"tags":["botany"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":42531,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":217,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1456587289},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1bdf34846fe88754ff56d2951a5f5837?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15728,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15728/ravi","reputation":21,"display_name":"ravi"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":38714,"edited":false,"creation_date":1442221657,"comment_id":64546,"body":"They seem to be non-standard terms. Manual/catalogue can refer to anything."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1nMw6.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16866,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16866/theforestecologist","reputation":1908,"display_name":"theforestecologist","accept_rate":14},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1456582763,"creation_date":1449988671,"body":"<p>A <strong>Flora<\/strong> describes plants and where they live. Floras typically include a dichotomous key for identification purposes and often times will include range maps as well. Floras are almost always designed to be simultaneously regionally constrained and regionally exhaustive/complete (i.e., includes all plants that grow in that region or at least all taxonomic divisions of specified taxa). <a href=\"http://www.herbarium.unc.edu/FloraArchives/WeakleyFlora_2012-Nov.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">See Example<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>A <strong>manual<\/strong> applies much more broadly to plants, and typically instructs you on a subject (e.g., identification/differentiation of species).  A manual does not need to be exhaustive and its scope is typically user defined (though often based on the scale/range of it's underlying subject). However, some have used the term manual to be more or less synonymous with Flora or otherwise similar document (e.g., see <a href=\"http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/30292#/summary\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>). <\/p>\n\n<p>A <strong>catalog<\/strong> is simply a listing of all species organized in some way. These are usually alphabetical (vs. taxonomically organized like a typical Flora). You will also never find a key in a catalog and will often find less phytographic detail. <\/p>\n\n<p>See Chapter 6 in <strong>Describing Species: Practical Taxonomic Procedure for Biologists<\/strong> by Judith Winston for further assistance.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41475,"question_id":38714,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1456582763}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/38714/what-is-the-difference-between-taxonomical-aids-flora-manual-and-catalogue","last_activity_date":1456582763,"creation_date":1442121781,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the difference between taxonomical aids Flora, Manual and Catalogue?","body":"<p>The three type of books mentioned above are taxonomical aids that offer information about species found in an area. However, the exact difference between them is not clear to me. Please explain.<\/p>\n","question_id":38714,"tags":["botany","taxonomy"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":263,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1442217523},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8042eb77f027eb0412e6249e955c23f3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":21929,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21929/jake","reputation":33,"display_name":"Jake"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TSuGp.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19521,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19521/jordi-zambrino","reputation":1024,"display_name":"Jordi Zambrino","accept_rate":83},"score":1,"post_id":43403,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455648700,"com