 are golden yellow.  In fact, I&#39;ve never seen a grove that&#39;s all orange, and aspens are common in the mountains here, wherever there is sufficient water."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8042eb77f027eb0412e6249e955c23f3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":21929,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21929/jake","reputation":33,"display_name":"Jake"},"score":1,"post_id":43405,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455651034,"comment_id":75132,"body":"The name of the .jpg is actually what started my confusion. To me, the bark and the way the leaves are concentrated at the top of the tree makes it look like quaking aspens. However, I don&#39;t think I&#39;ve ever seen the brown/reddish types of aspen before, which makes me think it&#39;s birch. Do aspen and birch often grow in the same area? Could it be a mix of the two?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":1,"post_id":43405,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8042eb77f027eb0412e6249e955c23f3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":21929,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21929/jake","reputation":33,"display_name":"Jake"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455651439,"comment_id":75133,"body":"Aspen and birch can definitely grow together. I also think that the distribution of leafs is a bit off compared to what I&#39;m used to in Birch, but I&#39;m not familiar with N. American birch species, or hybrids. The sturdie