science/bats/batsounds.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">Bat Detector<\/a>. There are few examples of Bat calls."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9f137c8bccd23ae845550c5e95c1e31b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4821,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4821/rodrigo","reputation":478,"display_name":"Rodrigo"},"score":1,"post_id":39015,"edited":false,"creation_date":1443570480,"comment_id":65469,"body":"Looks like the examples are not there anymore?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":2,"post_id":39015,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445579737,"comment_id":66847,"body":"This is a good question (+1), but I think you should re-record the sounds with the appropriate sampling frequency. With a sampling frequency of 48 kHz, you are likely to get lots of aliased high-frequency noises (in the absence of lowpass filtering) which could hamper data analysis."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/5Uayv.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8186,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8186/devashish-das","reputation":3783,"display_name":"Devashish Das","accept_rate":100},"score":1,"post_id":39015,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446201523,"comment_id":67324,"body":"Should I add a bounty for this??"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0f379b115b9090a1df9319f17574fa8b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":18925,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18925/mainma","reputation":133,"display_name":"MainMa"},"score":2,"post_id":39015,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/5Uayv.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8186,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/us